Page Macros:Substitutions "Macros with Substitutions" {
    Header "Macros that take arguments." BNF "Going up in the World." Para
    Text {More complicated macros can take arguments and
          substitute them into their output.  For example:}
    Indent {
        Bold {/foo Quux Fie}
    }
    Text {might be expanded out, and sent to the current world as:}
    Indent {
        Bold {:dances around yelling, "Fie, Quux, Fie!  Foo!  Bar!"}
    }
	Header "Substitutions"
	Text {When you define the text of what a macro will send, you can include
	      substitution codes that will be replaced by the arguments passed to
		  the macro at invocation time.  The codes are as follows:}
	Indent {
		Bold {%%} Pre {	} Text {a literal '%'.} Brk
		Bold {%1} Pre {	} Text {the first word passed to the macro.} Brk
		Bold {%9} Pre {	} Text {the ninth word passed to the macro.} Brk
		Bold {%*} Pre {	} Text {all args passed to the macro.} Brk
		Bold {%!} Pre {	} Text {all args passed to the macro, escaped for TCL.}
	}
	Text {For instance, the above } Bold {/foo}
	Text { example, was achieved with the following text macro script.}
	Indent {
		Bold {:dances around, yelling, "%2, %1, %2!  Foo!  Bar!"}
	}
	Header "Creating a Macro"
	Indent {
		Bullet
		Text {Open the Macro Editor with the } Link {Option->Macros} Macros:Dialog Text { menu item.} Brk
		Bullet
		Text {Click on the New button.} Brk
		Bullet
		Text {Enter a name for the new macro in the name field.} Brk
		Bullet
		Text {In the script field, enter the text to send, with substitutions.}
		  Brk
		Bullet
		Text {Click on the Add button.} Brk
		Bullet
		Text {Close the Macro Editor.}
	}
}
